section.para:
      			The following is an example of using Stereotype Annotation called @Service for ProductServiceImpl class,
      			a component of service layer.

                @Service
public class ProductServiceImpl extends GenericServiceImpl<Product, String>
        implements ProductService {
    @Resource
    MessageSource messageSource;
    @Resource
    ProductDao productDao;
}

			In the example above, the class name of the relevant class (starting with lower case) is set with bean name.
			Therefore, when searching for the relevant bean, you have to use productServiceImpl string.

          ProductService service = (ProductService) context.getBean("productServiceImpl");

      			If property is granted to the relevant annotation, you can define bean name as you want.

                @Service("productService")
public class ProductServiceImpl extends GenericServiceImpl<Product, String>;
        implements ProductService {
    @Resource
    MessageSource messageSource;
    @Resource
    ProductDao productDao;
}

				Spring Framework provides five
				scopes based on bean instance creation mechanism, and to define such bean scope,
				use @Scope as the following.




                @Scope("prototype")
@Service("productService")
public class ProductServiceImpl extends GenericServiceImpl<Product, String>
        implements ProductService {
    @Resource
    MessageSource messageSource;
    @Resource
    ProductDao productDao;
}

